05872nam a22009615i 9783110652086DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106520867 a10.1515/97831106520862doi  a(DE-B1597)517504  a(OCoLC)1153536376  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0020002bisacsh0483pa100qDE-101  aCE 2117qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17877:116161 aJanos, Damien, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAvicenna on the Ontology of Pure Quiddity /cDamien Janos. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XII, 762 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aScientia Graeco-Arabica ,x1868-7172 ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter I: Pure Quiddity in Context -- tChapter II: Quiddity in Itself and Mental Existence -- tChapter III: Quiddity in Itself in the Concrete World -- tChapter IV: The Special Ontological Mode of Quiddity in Itself -- tChapter V: The Divine Origin of Pure Quiddity -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1: The Avicennian terminology of pure quiddity -- tAppendix 2: The existence of pure quiddity: A list of textual references -- tAppendix 3: Quiddity and Avicenna’s matrices of distinctions -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names and Places -- tIndex of Technical Terms0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study focuses on the metaphysics of the great Arabic philosopher Avicenna (or Ibn Sīnā, d. 1037 C.E.). More specifically, it delves into Avicenna’s theory of quiddity or essence, a topic which seized the attention of thinkers both during the medieval and modern periods. Building on recent contributions in Avicennian studies, this book proposes a new and comprehensive interpretation of Avicenna’s theory of ‘the pure quiddity’ (also known as ‘the quiddity in itself’) and of its ontology. The study provides a careful philological analysis of key passages gleaned from the primary sources in Arabic and a close philosophical contextualization of Avicenna’s doctrines in light of the legacy of ancient Greek philosophy in Islam and the early development of Arabic philosophy (falsafah) and theology (kalām). The study pays particular attention to how Avicenna’s theory of quiddity relates to the ancient Greek philosophical discussion about the universals or common things and Mu’tazilite ontology. Its main thesis is that Avicenna articulated a sophisticated doctrine of the ontology of essence in light of Greek and Bahshamite sources, which decisively shaped subsequent intellectual history in Islam and the Latin West.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aAvicenna. 4aIslamische Philosophie. 4aPhilosophie des Mittelalters. 4aWesen. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAvicenna.  aHistory of Metaphysics.  aIslamic Philosophy.  aMedieval Philosophy.  aessence/quiddity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2020 Englishz978311070483908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studi